    "why": "End-user privacy, vendor data collection, and third-party sharing are three distinct aspects of the same underlying concern: who controls data about library patrons and library operations, and what that party can do with it. The three are best addressed together because they interact: tight end-user privacy language can be undermined by broad vendor data ownership, and tight data ownership can be undermined by broad third-party sharing rights. The Pro-Library Version anchors on applicable law (state library confidentiality laws in particular) and then adds specific protections that go beyond statutory minimums. Forty-eight hour breach notification is achievable in current commercial practice; institutions handling particularly sensitive data sometimes negotiate twenty-four hours.",
