export const README_TITLE = "Digital Content Licensing Clause Bank for Libraries";
export const README_SUBTITLE = "A working reference for libraries negotiating licenses to digital content, databases, and platforms.";
export const README_SECTIONS: ReadmeSection[] = [
  {
    "heading": "Intro",
    "body": [
      "Vendor templates for digital content licenses are typically drafted to favor the vendor. While that might be normal commercial practice, those templates aren't built for relationships with libraries. Your job as a library negotiator is to recognize patterns in your license, understand what the language means for your operation, and move the document toward language that is commercially reasonable for both sides. This Clause Bank offers better alternative language for use where the vendor's clause fails to meet library needs. The companion document (provided separately) explains the reasoning behind the suggested language and helps you decide which positions are worth holding."
    ]
  },
  {
    "heading": "Notes on Organization: Rows and Columns",
    "body": [
      "Each row covers one topic likely to appear in a contract. Three columns show the same clause in three versions, arranged left to right in the order you will use them during a negotiation.",
      "Common Pro-Vendor Language: the version you are likely to find in a vendor template. It favors the vendor in ways the rest of the row will help you see.",
      "Pro-Library Version: the version drafted to favor the library. These clauses aren't the polar opposite or mirror images of \"Pro-Vendor\", but are structured around commercial reasonableness and the realities of library obligations.",
      "Reasonable Fallback: language a negotiator on either side could defend as fair. This is where good-faith negotiations on the clause might land even where vendors are less willing to accept pushback.",
      "Why?: a short summary of why the changes are important to make. Further detail is written in the companion document.",
      "Watch For: common hidden cross-references and drafting patterns; language you might not catch on first pass.",
      "Clause ID: a stable identifier for each clause (such as GS-LG for License Grant). Use these to reference specific clauses across documents, in email exchanges, or when discussing the bank with colleagues.",
      "Companion Doc Ref: where to find the full discussion of this clause in the companion document."
    ]
  },
  {
    "heading": "Notes on Organization: Priority",
    "body": [
      "The five rightmost columns flag which clauses are highest priority for libraries with specific operational needs. Markers are sparse: only clauses where the need genuinely drives the priority are flagged. H means high priority; M means medium priority; blank means the clause is not specifically driven by that need (though it may still matter).",
      "Preservation: long-term reference value, archival mission, building durable collections. Primarily relevant for state libraries, consortia, and libraries with named special collections.",
      "Service Availability: uptime, patron-facing reliability, service level commitments, platform performance.",
      "Patron Privacy: reader confidentiality, state library privacy law compliance, professional ethics around patron data.",
      "Accessibility: ADA and Section 504 compliance, format-shifting for disability accommodation, WCAG-aligned platform requirements.",
      "Resource Sharing: ILL, consortial sharing, reciprocal access, walk-in users."
    ]
  },
  {
    "heading": "How You Can Use This Resource",
    "body": [
      "When presented with a new, or reviewing an existing, agreement, you can use this Clause Bank by searching for the topic or included language in the clauses you're reading. For each clause, find the matching row in the Clause Bank tab.",
      "Compare the vendor's language to the Common Pro-Vendor Language column. If the vendor's language matches, you are looking at a typical pro-vendor document. If it goes farther than what is in this column, the language is more aggressive; you can find tips for how to respond in the companion document.",
      "If you're actively negotiating, you can start with the Pro-Library Version as your opening counter for vendor terms. Use the Reasonable Fallback where necessary.",
      "Read the companion document for any clause where the stakes are muddy, where you're unsure which version to use, or where the vendor's reason for rejecting the edit isn't clear. If the vendor refuses to budge on a term, reference the separate Risk Assessment Scorecard for help in determining whether to accept the existing language or move on."
    ]
  },
  {
    "heading": "Working with the Risk Exposure Scorecard",
    "body": [
      "This Clause Bank is designed to work alongside the Risk Exposure Scorecard published in Library Futures's \"Understanding Confidentiality and Risk Assessment: A Reference Guide for Everyone, Everywhere.\" The Clause Bank tells you what the language should look like. The Scorecard tells you what to do when the vendor will not give you that language. The five Risk Factors in the Scorecard (Mission Alignment, Operational Dependency, Third Party Reputation, Financial Exposure, and Defensibility) map naturally to the considerations behind the priority columns, so use the two resources together: identify which clauses matter most for your library using the priority columns, then use the Scorecard to evaluate the specific language a vendor is offering when negotiations stall."
    ]
  },
  {
    "heading": "Color Coding",
    "body": [
      "The colors in this sheet are for delineation only and meant to help you track across a row. None of the three is inherently good or bad. Common Pro-Vendor Language is what you will typically see; Pro-Library Version is what you can credibly ask for; Reasonable Fallback is the likely landing place."
    ]
  },
  {
    "heading": "IMPORTANT!",
    "body": [
      "This workbook is a general reference, not legal advice. Leverage, jurisdiction, library type, and the specific resource being licensed all change what is reasonable in your situation. When in doubt, consult counsel.",
      "Vendors are usually licensees themselves. Most digital content vendors hold their own licenses from authors, creators, publishers, or aggregators, and their ability to grant certain rights, including perpetual access, text and data mining, interlibrary loan, accessibility format-shifting, and preservation copies, depends on what their upstream agreements permit. Some of what looks like one-sided drafting reflects real upstream constraints the vendor cannot unilaterally rewrite. The companion document discusses how to recognize the difference and how to negotiate productively when upstream rights are part of the picture.",
      "Some counterparties will not yield on certain provisions. This workbook is designed to help you decide whether language the vendor will not move on is acceptable to your library or whether it is a reason to walk. The Pro-Library Version and the Reasonable Fallback give you the alternatives; the priority columns and the companion document help you weigh them.",
      "Clauses interact, sometimes in unexpected ways. Review the full agreement, not just the clause you are focused on. The \"Watch For\" column and the companion document flag the most common interactions."
    ]
  },
  {
    "heading": "About",
    "body": [
      "This Clause Bank is part of a resource set published by Library Futures and is licensed under the CC-BY-4.0 attribution license. The companion document explains the reasoning behind each clause and informs difficult decisions. The Getting Started Guide (provided separately) covers terminology, the negotiation method, and reading paths organized around library priorities.",
      "© 2026 Library Futures / The Engelberg Center on Innovation Law & Policy",
      "Licensed for use under CC-BY-4.0"
    ]
  }
];

